# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: refinement-types
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] In computer science, **abstract interpretation** is a theory of sound approximation of the semantics of computer programs, based on monotonic functions over ordered sets, especially lattices.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] It can be viewed as a partial execution of a computer program which gains information about its semantics (e.g., control-flow, data-flow) without performing all the calculations.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] Abstract interpretation was formalized by the French computer scientist working couple Patrick Cousot and Radhia Cousot in the late 1970s.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] This section illustrates abstract interpretation by means of real-world, non-computing examples.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] Consider the people in a conference room.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] Assume a unique identifier for each person in the room, like a social security number in the United States.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] To prove that someone is not present, all one needs to do is see if their social security number is not on the list.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] Since two different people cannot have the same number, it is possible to prove or disprove the presence of a participant simply by looking up their number.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] However it is possible that only the names of attendees were registered.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] If the name of a person is not found in the list, we may safely conclude that that person was not present; but if it is, we cannot conclude definitely without further inquiries, due to the possibility of homonyms (for example, two people named John Smith).
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] Note that this imprecise information will still be adequate for most purposes, because homonyms are rare in practice.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] However, in all rigor, we cannot say for sure that somebody was present in the room; all we can say is that they were *possibly* here.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] If the person we are looking up is a criminal, we will issue an *alarm*; but there is of course the possibility of issuing a *false alarm*.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] Similar phenomena will occur in the analysis of programs.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] If we are only interested in some specific information, say, "was there a person of age n in the room?", keeping a list of all names and dates of births is unnecessary.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] We may safely and without loss of precision restrict ourselves to keeping a list of the participants' ages.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] If this is already too much to handle, we might keep only the age of the youngest, m and oldest person, M .
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] If the question is about an age strictly lower than m or strictly higher than M , then we may safely respond that no such participant was present.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] Otherwise, we may only be able to say that we do not know.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] In the case of computing, concrete, precise information is in general not computable within finite time and memory (see Rice's theorem and the halting problem).
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] One crucial requirement is to add enough vagueness so as to make problems manageable while still retaining enough precision for answering the important questions (such as "might the program crash?").
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] Given a programming or specification language, abstract interpretation consists of giving several semantics linked by relations of abstraction.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] A semantics is a mathematical characterization of a possible behavior of the program.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] The most precise semantics, describing very closely the actual execution of the program, are called the *concrete semantics*.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] More abstract semantics are then derived; for instance, one may consider only the set of reachable states in the executions (which amounts to considering the last states in finite traces).
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] The goal of static analysis is to derive a computable semantic interpretation at some point.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] For instance, one may choose to represent the state of a program manipulating integer variables by forgetting the actual values of the variables and only keeping their signs (+, − or 0).
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] For some elementary operations, such as multiplication, such an abstraction does not lose any precision: to get the sign of a product, it is sufficient to know the sign of the operands.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] For some other operations, the abstraction may lose precision: for instance, it is impossible to know the sign of a sum whose operands are respectively positive and negative.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] Sometimes a loss of precision is necessary to make the semantics decidable (see Rice's theorem and the halting problem).
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] In general, there is a compromise to be made between the precision of the analysis and its decidability (computability), or tractability (computational cost).
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] In practice the abstractions that are defined are tailored to both the program properties one desires to analyze, and to the set of target programs.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] The first large scale automated analysis of computer programs with abstract interpretation was motivated by the accident that resulted in the destruction of the first flight of the Ariane 5 rocket in 1996.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] Let L be an ordered set, called *concrete set*, and let $L'$ be another ordered set, called *abstract set*.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] These two sets are related to each other by defining total functions that map elements from one to the other.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] A function $\alpha$ is called an *abstraction function* if it maps an element x in the concrete set L to an element $\alpha (x)$ in the abstract set $L'$ .
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] That is, element $\alpha (x)$ in $L'$ is the *abstraction* of x in L .
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] A function $\gamma$ is called a *concretization function* if it maps an element $x'$ in the abstract set $L'$ to an element $\gamma (x')$ in the concrete set L .
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] That is, element $\gamma (x')$ in L is a *concretization* of $x'$ in $L'$ .
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] The concrete semantics f is a monotonic function from $L_{1}$ to $L_{2}$ .
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] Program semantics are generally described using fixed points in the presence of loops or recursive procedures.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] Suppose that L is a complete lattice and let f be a monotonic function from L into L .
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] Then, any $x'$ such that $f(x')\leq x'$ is an abstraction of the least fixed-point of f , which exists, according to the Knaster–Tarski theorem.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] The difficulty is now to obtain such an $x'$ .
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] In some cases, it is possible to define abstractions using Galois connections $(\alpha ,\gamma )$ where $\alpha$ is from L to $L'$ and $\gamma$ is from $L'$ to L .
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] This supposes the existence of best abstractions, which is not necessarily the case.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] For instance, if we abstract sets of couples $(x,y)$ of real numbers by enclosing convex polyhedra, there is no optimal abstraction to the disc defined by $x^{2}+y^{2}\leq 1$ .
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] One can assign to each variable x available at a given program point an interval $[L_{x},H_{x}]$ .
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] A state assigning the value $v(x)$ to variable x will be a concretization of these intervals if, for all x , we have $v(x)\in [L_{x},H_{x}]$ .
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] More complex formulas can be derived for multiplication, division, etc., yielding so-called interval arithmetics.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] With reasonable arithmetic types, the result for z should be zero.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] But if we do interval arithmetic starting from x in [0, 1], one gets z in [−1, +1].
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] While each of the operations taken individually was exactly abstracted, their composition isn't.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] The problem is evident: we did not keep track of the equality relationship between x and y; actually, this domain of intervals does not take into account any relationships between variables, and is thus a *non-relational domain*.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] Non-relational domains tend to be fast and simple to implement, but imprecise.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] and combinations thereof (such as the reduced product, cf. right picture).
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] When one chooses an abstract domain, one typically has to strike a balance between keeping fine-grained relationships, and high computational costs.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] There are several abstract domains suitable for various analyses of such variables.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] The *bitfield domain* treats each bit in a machine word separately, i.e., a word of width *n* is treated as an array of *n* abstract values.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] Further domains include the *signed interval domain* and the *unsigned interval domain*.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] All three of these domains support forwards and backwards abstract operators for common operations such as addition, shifts, xor, and multiplication.
[src:refinement-types/abstract-interpretation] These domains can be combined using the reduced product.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] It prescribes that software designers should define formal, precise and verifiable interface specifications for software components, which extend the ordinary definition of abstract data types with preconditions, postconditions and invariants.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] These specifications are referred to as "contracts", in accordance with a conceptual metaphor with the conditions and obligations of business contracts.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] The DbC approach assumes all *client components* that invoke an operation on a *server component* will meet the preconditions specified as required for that operation.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] The term was coined by Bertrand Meyer in connection with his design of the Eiffel programming language and first described in various articles starting in 1986 and the two successive editions (1988, 1997) of his book *Object-Oriented Software Construction*.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] Eiffel Software applied for trademark registration for *Design by Contract* in December 2003, and it was granted in December 2004.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] The current owner of this trademark is Eiffel Software.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] Design by contract has its roots in work on formal verification, formal specification and Hoare logic.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] The central idea of DbC is a metaphor on how elements of a software system collaborate with each other on the basis of mutual *obligations* and *benefits*.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] The contract is semantically equivalent to a Hoare triple which formalises the obligations.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] Many programming languages have facilities to make assertions like these.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] However, DbC considers these contracts to be so crucial to software correctness that they should be part of the design process.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] In effect, DbC advocates writing the assertions first.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] Contracts can be written by code comments, enforced by a test suite, or both, even if there is no special language support for contracts.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] Subclasses in an inheritance hierarchy are allowed to weaken preconditions (but not strengthen them) and strengthen postconditions and invariants (but not weaken them).
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] These rules approximate behavioural subtyping.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] All class relationships are between client classes and supplier classes.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] A client class is obliged to make calls to supplier features where the resulting state of the supplier is not violated by the client call.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] Subsequently, the supplier is obliged to provide a return state and data that does not violate the state requirements of the client.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] For instance, a supplier data buffer may require that data is present in the buffer when a delete feature is called.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] Subsequently, the supplier guarantees to the client that when a delete feature finishes its work, the data item will, indeed, be deleted from the buffer.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] Other design contracts are concepts of class invariant.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] The class invariant guarantees (for the local class) that the state of the class will be maintained within specified tolerances at the end of each feature execution.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] When using contracts, a supplier will verify that the contract conditions are satisfied—a practice known as offensive programming—the general idea being that code should "fail hard", with contract verification being the safety net.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] DbC's "fail hard" property simplifies the debugging of contract behavior, as the intended behaviour of each method is clearly specified.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] This approach differs substantially from that of defensive programming, where the supplier is responsible for figuring out what to do when a precondition is broken.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] More often than not, the supplier throws an exception to inform the client that the precondition has been broken, and in both cases—DbC and defensive programming alike—the client must figure out how to respond to that.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] In such cases, DbC makes the supplier's job easier.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] Design by contract can also facilitate code reuse, since the contract for each piece of code is fully documented.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] The contracts for a module can be regarded as a form of software documentation for the behavior of that module.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] Contract conditions should never be violated during execution of a bug-free program.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] Contracts are therefore typically only checked in debug mode during software development.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] Later at release, the contract checks are disabled to maximize performance.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] In many programming languages, contracts are implemented with assert.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] Asserts are by default compiled away in release mode in C/C++, and similarly deactivated in C# and Java.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] Launching the Python interpreter with "-O" (for "optimize") as an argument will likewise cause the Python code generator to not emit any bytecode for asserts.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] This effectively eliminates the run-time costs of asserts in production code—irrespective of the number and computational expense of asserts used in development—as no such instructions will be included in production by the compiler.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] Design by contract does not replace regular testing strategies, such as unit testing, integration testing and system testing.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] Rather, it complements external testing with internal self-tests that can be activated both for isolated tests and in production code during a test-phase.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] The advantage of internal self-tests is that they can detect errors before they manifest themselves as invalid results observed by the client.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] This leads to earlier and more specific error detection.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] The use of assertions can be considered to be a form of test oracle, a way of testing the design by contract implementation.
[src:refinement-types/design-by-contract] Further, the standard method combination in the Common Lisp Object System has the method qualifiers `:before`, `:after` and `:around` that allow writing contracts as auxiliary methods, among other uses.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] The central feature of **Hoare logic** is the **Hoare triple**.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] A triple describes how the execution of a piece of code changes the state of the computation.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] where P and Q are *assertions* and C is a *command*.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] P is named the *precondition* and Q the *postcondition*: when the precondition is met, executing the command establishes the postcondition.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Assertions are formulae in predicate logic.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Hoare logic provides axioms and inference rules for all the constructs of a simple imperative programming language.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] In addition to the rules for the simple language in Hoare's original paper, rules for other language constructs have been developed since then by Hoare and many other researchers.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] There are rules for concurrency, procedures, jumps, and pointers.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Using standard Hoare logic, only partial correctness can be proven.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Total correctness additionally requires termination, which can be proven separately or with an extended version of the While rule.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Thus, the intuitive reading of a Hoare triple is: Whenever P holds of the state before the execution of C , then Q will hold afterwards, or C does not terminate.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] In the latter case, there is no "after", so Q can be any statement at all.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Indeed, one can choose Q to be false to express that C does not terminate.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] The empty statement rule asserts that the skip statement does not change the state of the program, thus whatever holds true before skip also holds true afterwards.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] The assignment axiom states that, after the assignment, any predicate that was previously true for the right-hand side of the assignment now holds for the variable.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Formally, let P be an assertion in which the variable x is free.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] where $P[E/x]$ denotes the assertion P in which each free occurrence of x has been replaced by the expression E.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] The assignment axiom scheme means that the truth of $P[E/x]$ is equivalent to the after-assignment truth of P.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Thus, were $P[E/x]$ true before the assignment, by the assignment axiom, then P would be true afterwards.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Conversely, were $P[E/x]$ false (i.e. $\neg P[E/x]$ true) prior to the assignment statement, P must then be false afterwards.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] All preconditions that are not modified by the expression can be carried over to the postcondition.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] In the first example, assigning $y:=x+1$ does not change the fact that $x+1=43$ , so both statements may appear in the postcondition.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Formally, this result is obtained by applying the axiom schema with P being ( $y=43$ and $x+1=43$ ), which yields $P[(x+1)/y]$ being ( $x+1=43$ and $x+1=43$ ), which can in turn be simplified to the given precondition $x+1=43$ .
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] The assignment axiom scheme is equivalent to saying that to find the precondition, first take the post-condition and replace all occurrences of the left-hand side of the assignment with the right-hand side of the assignment.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] While a given postcondition P uniquely determines the precondition $P[E/x]$ , the converse is not true.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] are valid instances of the assignment axiom scheme.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] The assignment axiom proposed by Hoare *does not apply* when more than one name may refer to the same stored value.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] is wrong if x and y refer to the same variable (aliasing), although it is a proper instance of the assignment axiom scheme (with both $\{P\}$ and $\{P[2/x]\}$ being $\{y=3\}$ ).
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Another example is shown in the right box.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] The conditional rule states that a postcondition Q common to then and else part is also a postcondition of the whole if...endif statement.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] In the then and the else part, the unnegated and negated condition B can be added to the precondition P, respectively.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] The condition, B, must not have side effects.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] An example is given in the next section.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] This rule was not contained in Hoare's original publication.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] the conditional rule can be derived from the other Hoare rules.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] In a similar way, rules for other derived program constructs, like for loop, do...until loop, switch, break, continue can be reduced by program transformation to the rules from Hoare's original paper.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] This rule permits strengthening the precondition $P_{2}$ and/or to weaken the postcondition $Q_{2}$ .
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] It is used, e.g., to achieve literally identical postconditions for the then and the else part.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] The consequence rule is needed to strengthen the precondition $\{-1\leq x<15\}$ obtained from the assignment rule to $\{0\leq x<15\}$ required for the conditional rule.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] hence the consequence rule has to be applied with $P_{1}$ and $P_{2}$ being $\{x=15\}$ and $\{{\texttt {true}}\}$ , respectively, to strengthen again the precondition.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Informally, the effect of the consequence rule is to "forget" that $\{x=15\}$ is known at the entry of the else part, since the assignment rule used for the else part doesn't need that information.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Here P is the loop invariant, which is to be preserved by the loop body S.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] After the loop is finished, this invariant P still holds, and moreover $\neg B$ must have caused the loop to end.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] As in the conditional rule, B must not have side effects.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] which is easily obtained by the assignment rule.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Finally, the postcondition $\{\neg x<10\wedge x\leq 10\}$ can be simplified to $\{x=10\}$ .
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] which follows from the skip rule and the consequence rule.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] In fact, the strange program is *partially* correct: if it happened to terminate, it is certain that x must have contained (by chance) the value of a's square root.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] In all other cases, it will not terminate; therefore, it is not *totally* correct.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] If the above ordinary while rule is replaced by the following one, the Hoare calculus can also be used to prove total correctness, i.e., termination as well as partial correctness.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Commonly, square brackets are used here instead of curly braces to indicate the different notion of program correctness.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] In this rule, in addition to maintaining the loop invariant, one also proves termination by way of an expression t, called the loop variant, whose value strictly decreases with respect to a well-founded relation < on some domain set D during each iteration.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Since < is well-founded, a strictly decreasing chain of members of D can have only finite length, so t cannot keep decreasing forever.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Given the loop invariant P, the condition B must imply that t is not a minimal element of D, for otherwise the body S could not decrease t any further, i.e. the premise of the rule would be false.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] the while rule for total correctness can be applied with e.g.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] Informally speaking, we have to prove that the distance $10-x$ decreases in every loop cycle, while it always remains non-negative; this process can go on only for a finite number of cycles.
[src:refinement-types/hoare-logic] For the second example of the previous section, of course, no expression t can be found that is decreased by the empty loop body, hence termination cannot be proved.
[src:refinement-types/refinement-type] In type theory, a **refinement type** is a type endowed with a predicate which is assumed to hold for any element of the refined type.
[src:refinement-types/refinement-type] Refinement types are thus related to behavioral subtyping.
[src:refinement-types/refinement-type] The concept of refinement types was first introduced in Freeman and Pfenning's 1991 *Refinement types for ML*, which presents a type system for a subset of Standard ML.
[src:refinement-types/refinement-type] The type system "preserves the decidability of ML's type inference" whilst still "allowing more errors to be detected at compile-time".
[src:refinement-types/refinement-type] In more recent times, refinement type systems have been developed (primary in academia) for languages such as Haskell, TypeScript, Rust, and as libraries for real world usage in Scala.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] In computer science and mathematical logic, **satisfiability modulo theories** (**SMT**) is the problem of determining whether a mathematical formula is satisfiable.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] It generalizes the Boolean satisfiability problem (SAT) to more complex formulas involving real numbers, integers, and/or various data structures such as lists, arrays, bit vectors, and strings.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The name is derived from the fact that these expressions are interpreted within ("modulo") a certain formal theory in first-order logic with equality (often disallowing quantifiers).
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] **SMT solvers** are tools that aim to solve the SMT problem for a practical subset of inputs.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] SMT solvers such as Z3 and cvc5 have been used as a building block for a wide range of applications across computer science, including in automated theorem proving, program analysis, program verification, and software testing.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Since Boolean satisfiability is already NP-complete, the SMT problem is typically NP-hard, and for many theories it is undecidable.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Researchers study which theories or subsets of theories lead to a decidable SMT problem and the computational complexity of decidable cases.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The resulting decision procedures are often implemented directly in SMT solvers; see, for instance, the decidability of Presburger arithmetic.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] SMT can be thought of as a constraint satisfaction problem and thus a certain formalized approach to constraint programming.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Formally speaking, an SMT instance is a formula in first-order logic, where some function and predicate symbols have additional interpretations, and SMT is the problem of determining whether such a formula is satisfiable.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] In other words, imagine an instance of the Boolean satisfiability problem (SAT) in which some of the binary variables are replaced by predicates over a suitable set of non-binary variables.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] A predicate is a binary-valued function of non-binary variables.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Example predicates include linear inequalities (e.g., $3x+2y-z\geq 4$ ) or equalities involving uninterpreted terms and function symbols (e.g., $f(f(u,v),v)=f(u,v)$ where f is some unspecified function of two arguments).
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] These predicates are classified according to each respective theory assigned.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Other theories include the theories of arrays and list structures (useful for modeling and verifying computer programs), and the theory of bit vectors (useful in modeling and verifying hardware designs).
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Subtheories are also possible: for example, difference logic is a sub-theory of linear arithmetic in which each inequality is restricted to have the form $x-y>c$ for variables x and y and constant c .
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The examples above show the use of linear integer arithmetic over inequalities.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Most SMT solvers support only quantifier-free fragments of their logics.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] There is substantial overlap between SMT solving and automated theorem proving (ATP).
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Generally, automated theorem provers focus on supporting full first-order logic with quantifiers, whereas SMT solvers focus more on supporting various theories (interpreted predicate symbols).
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] ATPs excel at problems with lots of quantifiers, whereas SMT solvers do well on large problems without quantifiers.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The line is blurry enough that some ATPs participate in SMT-COMP, while some SMT solvers participate in CASC.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] An SMT instance is a generalization of a Boolean SAT instance in which various sets of variables are replaced by predicates from a variety of underlying theories.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] SMT formulas provide a much richer modeling language than is possible with Boolean SAT formulas.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] For example, an SMT formula allows one to model the datapath operations of a microprocessor at the word rather than the bit level.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] By comparison, answer set programming is also based on predicates (more precisely, on atomic sentences created from atomic formulas).
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Unlike SMT, answer-set programs do not have quantifiers, and cannot easily express constraints such as linear arithmetic or difference logic—answer set programming is best suited to Boolean problems that reduce to the free theory of uninterpreted functions.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Implementing 32-bit integers as bitvectors in answer set programming suffers from most of the same problems that early SMT solvers faced: "obvious" identities such as *x* + *y* = *y* + *x* are difficult to deduce.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Constraint logic programming does provide support for linear arithmetic constraints, but within a completely different theoretical framework.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] SMT solvers have also been extended to solve formulas in higher-order logic.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] This approach, which is referred to as *the eager approach* (or *bitblasting*), has its merits: by pre-processing the SMT formula into an equivalent Boolean SAT formula existing Boolean SAT solvers can be used "as-is" and their performance and capacity improvements leveraged over time.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] This approach is referred to as *the lazy approach*.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Dubbed DPLL(T), this architecture gives the responsibility of Boolean reasoning to the DPLL-based SAT solver which, in turn, interacts with a solver for theory T through a well-defined interface.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The theory solver only needs to worry about checking the feasibility of conjunctions of theory predicates passed on to it from the SAT solver as it explores the Boolean search space of the formula.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] For this integration to work well, however, the theory solver must be able to participate in propagation and conflict analysis, i.e., it must be able to infer new facts from already established facts, as well as to supply succinct explanations of infeasibility when theory conflicts arise.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] In other words, the theory solver must be incremental and backtrackable.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Since full first-order logic is only semidecidable, one line of research attempts to find efficient decision procedures for fragments of first-order logic such as effectively propositional logic.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Examples of monotonic theories include graph reachability, collision detection for convex hulls, minimum cuts, and computation tree logic.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Every Datalog program can be interpreted as a monotonic theory.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Most of the common SMT approaches support decidable theories.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] However, many real-world systems, such as an aircraft and its behavior, can only be modelled by means of non-linear arithmetic over the real numbers involving transcendental functions.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Such problems are, however, undecidable in general.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] (On the other hand, the theory of real closed fields, and thus the full first order theory of the real numbers, are decidable using quantifier elimination.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] This is due to Alfred Tarski.) The first order theory of the natural numbers with addition (but not multiplication), called Presburger arithmetic, is also decidable.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Since multiplication by constants can be implemented as nested additions, the arithmetic in many computer programs can be expressed using Presburger arithmetic, resulting in decidable formulas.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The table below summarizes some of the features of the many available SMT solvers.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The column "SMT-LIB" indicates compatibility with the SMT-LIB language; many systems marked 'yes' may support only older versions of SMT-LIB, or offer only partial support for the language.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The column "CVC" indicates support for the CVC language.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The column "DIMACS" indicates support for the DIMACS format.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Projects differ not only in features and performance, but also in the viability of the surrounding community, its ongoing interest in a project, and its ability to contribute documentation, fixes, tests and enhancements.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Focuses on generating high quality, compact interpolants.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Toolbox for strategic and parallel SMT solving consisting of a collection of SMT compliant implementations.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] There are multiple attempts to describe a standardized interface to SMT solvers (and automated theorem provers, a term often used synonymously).
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The most prominent is the SMT-LIB standard, which provides a language based on S-expressions.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Other standardized formats commonly supported are the DIMACS format supported by many Boolean SAT solvers, and the CVC format used by the CVC automated theorem prover.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The SMT-LIB format also comes with a number of standardized benchmarks and has enabled a yearly competition between SMT solvers called SMT-COMP.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Initially, the competition took place during the Computer Aided Verification conference (CAV), but as of 2020 the competition is hosted as part of the SMT Workshop, which is affiliated with the International Joint Conference on Automated Reasoning (IJCAR).
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] SMT solvers are useful both for verification, proving the correctness of programs, software testing based on symbolic execution, and for synthesis, generating program fragments by searching over the space of possible programs.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Outside of software verification, SMT solvers have also been used for type inference and for modelling theoretic scenarios, including modelling actor beliefs in nuclear arms control.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Computer-aided verification of computer programs often uses SMT solvers.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] A common technique is to translate preconditions, postconditions, loop conditions, and assertions into SMT formulas in order to determine if all properties can hold.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] There are many verifiers built on top of the Z3 SMT solver.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Boogie is an intermediate verification language that uses Z3 to automatically check simple imperative programs.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The VCC verifier for concurrent C uses Boogie, as well as Dafny for imperative object-based programs, Chalice for concurrent programs, and Spec# for C#.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] F* is a dependently typed language that uses Z3 to find proofs; the compiler carries these proofs through to produce proof-carrying bytecode.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The Viper verification infrastructure encodes verification conditions to Z3.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The sbv library provides SMT-based verification of Haskell programs, and lets the user choose among a number of solvers such as Z3, ABC, Boolector, cvc5, MathSAT and Yices.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] There are also many verifiers built on top of the Alt-Ergo SMT solver.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Many SMT solvers implement a common interface format called SMTLIB2 (such files usually have the extension "`.smt2`").
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The LiquidHaskell tool implements a refinement type based verifier for Haskell that can use any SMTLIB2 compliant solver, e.g. cvc5, MathSat, or Z3.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] An important application of SMT solvers is symbolic execution for analysis and testing of programs (e.g., concolic testing), aimed particularly at finding security vulnerabilities.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Example tools in this category include SAGE from Microsoft Research, KLEE, S2E, and Triton.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] SMT solvers that have been used for symbolic-execution applications include Z3, STP Archived 2015-04-06 at the Wayback Machine, the Z3str family of solvers, and Boolector.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] SMT solvers have been integrated with proof assistants, including Rocq and Isabelle/HOL.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] SMT solvers are a core building block in program synthesis, the automated generation of programs from specifications.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] A prominent approach is counterexample-guided inductive synthesis (CEGIS), in which a synthesiser proposes a candidate program that is verified by an SMT solver; counterexamples from failed checks guide the synthesiser until a correct solution is found.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] A related application is automatic program repair: given a buggy program and a test suite, an SMT formula is constructed whose solution yields a patch.
[src:refinement-types/satisfiability-modulo-theories] For example, Nopol encodes the problem of finding a repaired conditional expression as an SMT instance, translating the solution back into a source-code patch for Java programs.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In programming language theory, **subtyping** (also called **subtype polymorphism** or **inclusion polymorphism**) is a form of type polymorphism.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] A ***subtype*** is a datatype that is related to another datatype (the ***supertype***) by some notion of substitutability, meaning that program elements (typically subroutines or functions), written to operate on elements of the supertype, can also operate on elements of the subtype.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] If S is a subtype of T, the subtyping relation (written as *S* <: *T*, *S* ⊑ *T*, or *S* ≤: *T* ) means that any term of type S can *safely be used* in *any context* where a term of type T is expected.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The precise semantics of subtyping here crucially depends on the particulars of how *"safely be used"* and *"any context"* are defined by a given type formalism or programming language.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The type system of a programming language essentially defines its own subtyping relation, which may well be trivial, should the language support no (or very little) conversion mechanisms.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Due to the subtyping relation, a term may belong to more than one type.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Subtyping is therefore a form of type polymorphism.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In object-oriented programming the term 'polymorphism' is commonly used to refer solely to this *subtype polymorphism*, while the techniques of parametric polymorphism would be considered *generic programming*.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Functional programming languages often allow the subtyping of records.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Consequently, simply typed lambda calculus extended with record types is perhaps the simplest theoretical setting in which a useful notion of subtyping may be defined and studied.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Because the resulting calculus allows terms to have more than one type, it is no longer a "simple" type theory.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Since functional programming languages, by definition, support function literals, which can also be stored in records, records types with subtyping provide some of the features of object-oriented programming.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Typically, functional programming languages also provide some, usually restricted, form of parametric polymorphism.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In a theoretical setting, it is desirable to study the interaction of the two features; a common theoretical setting is system F<:.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Various calculi that attempt to capture the theoretical properties of object-oriented programming may be derived from system F<:.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The concept of subtyping is related to the linguistic notions of hyponymy and holonymy.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] It is also related to the concept of bounded quantification in mathematical logic (see Order-sorted logic).
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In a number of object-oriented languages, subtyping is called **interface inheritance**, with inheritance referred to as *implementation inheritance*.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The notion of subtyping in programming languages dates back to the 1960s; it was introduced in Simula derivatives.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The first formal treatments of subtyping were given by John C.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Reynolds in 1980 who used category theory to formalize implicit conversions, and Luca Cardelli (1985).
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The concept of subtyping has gained visibility (and synonymy with polymorphism in some circles) with the mainstream adoption of object-oriented programming.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In this context, the principle of safe substitution is often called the Liskov substitution principle, after Barbara Liskov who popularized it in a keynote address at a conference on object-oriented programming in 1987.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Because it must consider mutable objects, the ideal notion of subtyping defined by Liskov and Jeannette Wing, called behavioral subtyping is considerably stronger than what can be implemented in a type checker.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] A simple practical example of subtypes is shown in the diagram.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The type "bird" has three subtypes "duck", "cuckoo" and "ostrich".
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Conceptually, each of these is a variety of the basic type "bird" that inherits many "bird" characteristics but has some specific differences.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The UML notation is used in this diagram, with open-headed arrows showing the direction and type of the relationship between the supertype and its subtypes.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] As a more practical example, a language might allow integer values to be used wherever floating point values are expected (`Integer` <: `Float`), or it might define a generic type Number as a common supertype of integers and the reals.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In this second case, we only have `Integer` <: `Number` and `Float` <: `Number`, but `Integer` and `Float` are not subtypes of each other.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Programmers may take advantage of subtyping to write code in a more abstract manner than would be possible without it.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] If integer and real are both subtypes of `Number`, and an operator of comparison with an arbitrary Number is defined for both types, then values of either type can be passed to this function.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] However, the very possibility of implementing such an operator highly constrains the Number type (for example, one can't compare an integer with a complex number), and actually only comparing integers with integers, and reals with reals, makes sense.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Rewriting this function so that it would only accept 'x' and 'y' of the same type requires bounded polymorphism.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Subtyping enables a given type to be substituted for another type or abstraction.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Subtyping is said to establish an is-a relationship between the subtype and some existing abstraction, either implicitly or explicitly, depending on language support.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The relationship can be expressed explicitly via inheritance in languages that support inheritance as a subtyping mechanism.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The following C++ code establishes an explicit inheritance relationship between classes **B** and **A**, where **B** is both a subclass and a subtype of **A**, and can be used as an **A** wherever a **B** is specified (via a reference, a pointer or the object itself).
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The following python code establishes an explicit inheritance relationship between classes *B* and *A*, where *B* is both a subclass and a subtype of *A*, and can be used as an *A* wherever a *B* is required.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The following example, *type(a)* is a "regular" type, and *type(type(a))* is a metatype.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] While as distributed all types have the same metatype (*PyType_Type*, which is also its own metatype), this is not a requirement.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The type of classic classes, known as *types.ClassType*, can also be considered a distinct metatype.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In Java, **is-a** relation between the type parameters of one class or interface and the type parameters of another are determined by the extends and implements clauses.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Using the `Collections` classes, `ArrayList<E>` implements `List<E>`, and `List<E>` extends `Collection<E>`.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] So `ArrayList<String>` is a subtype of `List<String>`, which is a subtype of `Collection<String>`.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The subtyping relationship is preserved between the types automatically.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In type theory the concept of *subsumption* is used to define or evaluate whether a type **S** is a subtype of type **T**.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The set can be described *extensionally* by listing all the values, or it can be described *intensionally* by stating the membership of the set by a predicate over a domain of possible values.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In common programming languages enumeration types are defined extensionally by listing values.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] User-defined types like records (structs, interfaces) or classes are defined intensionally by an explicit type declaration or by using an existing value, which encodes type information, as a prototype to be copied or extended.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In discussing the concept of subsumption, the set of values of a type is indicated by writing its name in mathematical italics: T.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The type, viewed as a predicate over a domain, is indicated by writing its name in bold: **T**.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The conventional symbol **<:** means "is a subtype of", and **:>** means "is a supertype of".
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In terms of information specificity, a subtype is considered more specific than any one of its supertypes, because it holds at least as much information as each of them.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] This may increase the applicability, or *relevance* of the subtype (the number of situations where it can be accepted or introduced), as compared to its "more general" supertypes.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The disadvantage of having this more detailed information is that it represents incorporated choices which reduce the *prevalence* of the subtype (the number of situations which are able to generate or produce it).
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In the context of subsumption, the type definitions can be expressed using Set-builder notation, which uses a predicate to define a set.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Predicates can be defined over a domain (set of possible values) D.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Predicates are partial functions that compare values to selection criteria.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] For example: "is an integer value greater than or equal to 100 and less than 200?".
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] If a value matches the criteria then the function returns the value.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] If not, the value is not selected, and nothing is returned.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The predicate $\mathbf {T} =P_{T}$ is applied alongside $P_{s}$ as part of the compound predicate **S** defining S.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The two predicates are *conjoined*, so both must be true for a value to be selected.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] For example: there is a subfamily of cat species called *Felinae*, which is part of the family *Felidae*.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The genus *Felis*, to which the domestic cat species *Felis catus* belongs, is part of that subfamily.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The conjunction of predicates has been expressed here through application of the second predicate over the domain of values conforming to the first predicate.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Viewed as types, **Felis <: Felinae <: Felidae**.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] If **T** subsumes **S** (**T :> S**) then a procedure, function or expression given a value $s\in S$ as an operand (parameter value or term) will therefore be able to operate over that value as one of type **T**, because $s\in T$ .
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In the example above, we could expect the function *ofSubfamily* to be applicable to values of all three types **Felidae**, **Felinae** and **Felis**.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Type theorists make a distinction between **nominal subtyping**, in which only types declared in a certain way may be subtypes of each other, and **structural subtyping**, in which the structure of two types determines whether or not one is a subtype of the other.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] This so-called *duck typing* is common in dynamically typed object-oriented languages.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Sound structural subtyping rules for types other than object types are also well known.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The subtyping induced by subclassing in an object-oriented language is usually inclusive; subtyping relations that relate integers and floating-point numbers, which are represented differently, are usually coercive.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In almost all type systems that define a subtyping relation, it is reflexive (meaning *A* <: *A* for any type *A*) and transitive (meaning that if *A* <: *B* and *B* <: *C* then *A* <: *C*).
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Types of records give rise to the concepts of *width* and *depth* subtyping.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] These express two different ways of obtaining a new type of record that allows the same operations as the original record type.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Recall that a record is a collection of (named) fields.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Since a subtype is a type which allows all operations allowed on the original type, a record subtype should support the same operations on the fields as the original type supported.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] One kind of way to achieve such support, called *width subtyping*, adds more fields to the record.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] More formally, every (named) field appearing in the width supertype will appear in the width subtype.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Thus, any operation feasible on the supertype will be supported by the subtype.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The second method, called *depth subtyping*, replaces the various fields with their subtypes.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] That is, the fields of the subtype are subtypes of the fields of the supertype.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Since any operation supported for a field in the supertype is supported for its subtype, any operation feasible on the record supertype is supported by the record subtype.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Subtyping of records can be defined in System F<:, which combines parametric polymorphism with subtyping of record types and is a theoretical basis for many functional programming languages that support both features.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Some systems also support subtyping of labeled disjoint union types (such as algebraic data types).
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The rule for width subtyping is reversed: every tag appearing in the width subtype must appear in the width supertype.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] If *T*1 → *T*2 is a function type, then a subtype of it is any function type *S*1 → *S*2 with the property that *T*1 <: *S*1 and *S*2 <: *T*2.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The parameter type of *S*1 → *S*2 is said to be contravariant because the subtyping relation is reversed for it, whereas the return type is covariant.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Informally, this reversal occurs because the refined type is "more liberal" in the types it accepts and "more conservative" in the type it returns.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In languages that allow side effects, like most object-oriented languages, subtyping is generally not sufficient to guarantee that a function can be safely used in the context of another.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Liskov's work in this area focused on behavioral subtyping, which besides the type system safety discussed in this article also requires that subtypes preserve all invariants guaranteed by the supertypes in some contract.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] This definition of subtyping is generally undecidable, so it cannot be verified by a type checker.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The subtyping of mutable references is similar to the treatment of parameter values and return values.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Write-only references (or *sinks*) are contravariant, like parameter values; read-only references (or *sources*) are covariant, like return values.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Mutable references which act as both sources and sinks are invariant.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Subtyping and inheritance are independent (orthogonal) relationships.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] They may coincide, but none is a special case of the other.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The first case is illustrated by independent types, such as `Boolean` and `Float`.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The second case can be illustrated by the relationship between `Int32` and `Int64`.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In most object oriented programming languages, `Int64` are unrelated by inheritance to `Int32`.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] However `Int32` can be considered a subtype of `Int64` since any 32 bit integer value can be promoted into a 64 bit integer value.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The third case is a consequence of function subtyping input contravariance.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Assume a super class of type *T* having a method *m* returning an object of the same type (*i.e.* the type of *m* is *T* → *T*, also note that the first parameter of *m* is this/self) and a derived class type *S* from *T*.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] By inheritance, the type of *m* in *S* is *S* → *S*.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In order for *S* to be a subtype of *T* the type of *m* in *S* must be a subtype of the type of *m* in *T* , in other words: *S* → *S* ≤: *T* → *T*.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] By bottom-up application of the function subtyping rule, this means: *S* ≤: *T* and *T* ≤: *S*, which is only possible if *S* and *T* are the same.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Since inheritance is an irreflexive relation, *S* can't be a subtype of *T*.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Subtyping and inheritance are compatible when all inherited fields and methods of the derived type have types which are subtypes of the corresponding fields and methods from the inherited type .
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] In coercive subtyping systems, subtypes are defined by explicit type conversion functions from subtype to supertype.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] For each subtyping relationship (*S* <: *T*), a coercion function *coerce*: *S* → *T* is provided, and any object *s* of type *S* is regarded as the object *coerce**S* → *T*(*s*) of type *T*.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] A coercion function may be defined by composition: if *S* <: *T* and *T* <: *U* then *s* may be regarded as an object of type *u* under the compound coercion (*coerce**T* → *U* ∘ *coerce**S* → *T*).
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The type coercion from a type to itself *coerce**T* → *T* is the identity function *id*T.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Coercion functions for records and disjoint union subtypes may be defined componentwise; in the case of width-extended records, type coercion simply discards any components which are not defined in the supertype.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The type coercion for function types may be given by *f'*(*t*) = *coerce**S*2 → *T*2(*f*(*coerce**T*1 → *S*1(*t*))), reflecting the contravariance of parameter values and covariance of return values.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] The coercion function is uniquely determined given the subtype and supertype.
[src:refinement-types/subtyping] Thus, when multiple subtyping relationships are defined, one must be careful to guarantee that all type coercions are coherent.
